{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:35:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:35:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22624"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22624"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.11,0.24,0.46,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113276"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95309"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"904"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"41888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41889"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46853"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113276"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of crampy abdominal pain and distension. She has not opened her bowels for three days and has been vomiting intermittently. She has no significant medical history apart from an appendicectomy three years ago. She takes no regular medications except the oral contraceptive pill. She does not smoke and drinks about two glasses of wine at weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 88/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. Her abdomen is uniformly distended, resonant to percussion and soft with numerous high-pitched bowel sounds. There is no localised tenderness or palpable masses. Digital rectal examination reveals an empty rectum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is arranged (Images 1 and 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paralytic ileus","Sigmoid volvulus","Caecal volvulus","Small bowel adhesion-obstruction","Carcinoma of the colon"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiological features of large bowel obstruction. The CT scan demonstrates dilated loops of large bowel with a stenosing lesion in the sigmoid colon, which is highly suggestive of an obstructing colorectal carcinoma (Image). While colorectal cancer is less common in younger patients, it should always be considered when there is evidence of a stenosing colonic lesion, particularly in the absence of other predisposing factors for benign causes of obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the colon\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the CT findings of a stenosing lesion in the sigmoid colon. The presence of a discrete narrowing with proximal bowel dilatation is characteristic of a malignant stricture. Despite the patient\u0027s young age and lack of typical risk factors, colorectal cancer can occur in younger adults and may present with obstruction as the initial manifestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst there has been an overall decrease in the incidence of colorectal cancer - largely as a result of screening programs - the disease is being seen with increased frequency in the younger age groups (\u0026lt;50 years). In Australia, the incidence of colon cancer in individuals aged 20\u201329 years increased by 9% per year between 2004 and 2014. The reasons for this increase are not fully understood, but lifestyle, diet and obesity are almost certainly contributory factors. Another possible explanation could be the detection of the disease in patients in the 45 - 50 year age group, who are now eligible for the screening program. In Australia, the National Bowel Cancer Screening Program now offers free screening to individuals aged 45 - 74 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalytic ileus\u003C/strong\u003E would present with absent or hypoactive bowel sounds rather than the high-pitched sounds heard in this case. Additionally, CT would show generalised bowel dilatation without a transition point or stenosing lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in elderly patients with chronic constipation or neuropsychiatric conditions. On CT, it would show a characteristic \u0027coffee bean\u0027 sign or \u0027whirl sign\u0027 at the point of torsion, rather than a stenosing lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E would cause right-sided colonic obstruction and typically shows a dilated caecum in an abnormal position (often in the left upper quadrant) with a \u0027bird\u0027s beak\u0027 appearance at the point of torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel adhesion-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E is a common complication following abdominal surgery. However, the CT findings clearly show large bowel obstruction with a stenosing lesion in the sigmoid colon, not the dilated small bowel loops with a transition point that would be expected in adhesional small bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Large bowel obstruction in younger patients should raise suspicion for colorectal malignancy, even without typical risk factors.","CT imaging showing a stenosing lesion with proximal bowel dilatation is characteristic of obstructing colorectal carcinoma.","Previous abdominal surgery is a risk factor for adhesional small bowel obstruction but does not typically cause large bowel obstruction."],"references":["Araghi M. Soerjomataram I, Bardot A, et al. Changes in colorectal cancer incidence in seven high-income countries: a population-based study. Lancet Gastroenterol Hepatol 2019; 4: 511\u201318","Jones J, Walizai T, Campos A, et al. Large bowel obstruction. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 04 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-6335","Schafer E J, Sung H, Star J, et al. Colorectal Cancer Incidence in US Adults After Recommendations for Earlier Screening. JAMA 2025 Aug 4.  doi: 10.1001/jama"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95309"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22624"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22002"},{"type":"media","id":"22003"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22099"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22002"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rJPO4LjPAn81L5TbP4pHJdaeLYtrXo.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rJPO4LjPAn81L5TbP4pHJdaeLYtrXo.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":846,"height":591}},{"type":"media","id":"22003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22003"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/IFTibPsVbsZnG5IAYGeBptjNHl1FSD.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/IFTibPsVbsZnG5IAYGeBptjNHl1FSD.jpg